name: audio0.wav
speaker: SPEAKER_01
text: I'm Jim Lehrer of the PBS NewsHour, and I welcome you to the first of the 2012 presidential debates between President Barack Obama, the Democratic nominee, and former Massachusetts Governor Mitt Romney, the Republican nominee.

name: audio1.wav
speaker: SPEAKER_01
text: This debate and the next three, two presidential, one vice presidential, are sponsored by the Commission on Presidential Debates.

name: audio2.wav
speaker: SPEAKER_01
text: Tonight's 90 minutes will be about domestic issues and will follow a format designed by the Commission.

name: audio3.wav
speaker: SPEAKER_01
text: There will be six roughly 15-minute segments with two-minute answers for the first question, then open discussion for the remainder of each segment.

name: audio4.wav
speaker: SPEAKER_01
text: Thousands of people offered suggestions on segment subjects or questions via the internet and other means, but I made the final selections, and for the record, they were not submitted for approval to the Commission or the candidates.

name: audio5.wav
speaker: SPEAKER_01
text: The segments, as I announced in advance, will be three on the economy, and one each on health care, the role of government, and governing, with an emphasis throughout on differences, specifics, and choices.

name: audio6.wav
speaker: SPEAKER_01
text: Both candidates will also have two-minute closing statements.

name: audio7.wav
speaker: SPEAKER_01
text: The audience here in the hall has promised to remain silent.

name: audio8.wav
speaker: SPEAKER_01
text: No cheers, applause, boos, hisses, among other noisy, distracting things, so we may all concentrate on what the candidates have to say.

name: audio9.wav
speaker: SPEAKER_01
text: There is a noise exception right now, though, as we welcome President Obama and Governor Romney.

name: audio10.wav
speaker: SPEAKER_02
text: Jim.

name: audio11.wav
speaker: SPEAKER_01
text: Gentlemen, welcome to you both.

name: audio12.wav
speaker: SPEAKER_01
text: Let's start the economy, segment one, and let's begin with jobs.

name: audio13.wav
speaker: SPEAKER_01
text: What are the major differences between the two of you about how you would go about creating new jobs?

name: audio14.wav
speaker: SPEAKER_01
text: You have two minutes.

name: audio15.wav
speaker: SPEAKER_01
text: Each of you have two minutes to start.

name: audio16.wav
speaker: SPEAKER_01
text: A coin toss is determined.

name: audio17.wav
speaker: SPEAKER_01
text: Mr. President, you go first.

name: audio18.wav
speaker: SPEAKER_00
text: The President Well, thank you very much, Jim, for this opportunity.

name: audio19.wav
speaker: SPEAKER_00
text: I want to thank Governor Romney and the University of Denver for your hospitality.

name: audio20.wav
speaker: SPEAKER_00
text: There are a lot of points I want to make tonight, but the most important one is that 20 years ago I became the luckiest man on Earth because Michelle Obama agreed to marry me.

name: audio21.wav
speaker: SPEAKER_00
text: And so I just want to wish

name: audio22.wav
speaker: SPEAKER_00
text: sweetie, you happy anniversary, and let you know that a year from now we will not be celebrating it in front of 40 million people.

name: audio23.wav
speaker: SPEAKER_00
text: Four years ago, we went through the worst financial crisis since the Great Depression.

name: audio24.wav
speaker: SPEAKER_00
text: Millions of jobs were lost.

name: audio25.wav
speaker: SPEAKER_00
text: The auto industry was on the brink of collapse.

name: audio26.wav
speaker: SPEAKER_00
text: The financial system had frozen up.

name: audio27.wav
speaker: SPEAKER_00
text: And because of the resilience and the determination of the American people, we've begun to fight our way back.

name: audio28.wav
speaker: SPEAKER_00
text: Over the last 30 months, we've seen 5 million jobs in the private sector created.

name: audio29.wav
speaker: SPEAKER_00
text: The auto industry has come roaring back, and housing has begun to rise.

name: audio30.wav
speaker: SPEAKER_00
text: But we all know that we've still got a lot of work to do.

name: audio31.wav
speaker: SPEAKER_00
text: And so the question here tonight is not where we've been, but where we're going.

name: audio32.wav
speaker: SPEAKER_00
text: Governor Romney has a perspective that says if we cut taxes,

name: audio33.wav
speaker: SPEAKER_00
text: skewed towards the wealthy and rollback regulations that we'll be better off.

name: audio34.wav
speaker: SPEAKER_00
text: I've got a different view.

name: audio35.wav
speaker: SPEAKER_00
text: I think we've got to invest in education and training.

name: audio36.wav
speaker: SPEAKER_00
text: I think it's important for us to develop new sources of energy here in America, that we change our tax code to make sure that we're helping small businesses and companies that are investing here in the United States, that we take some of the money that we're saving as we wind down two wars to rebuild America.

name: audio37.wav
speaker: SPEAKER_00
text: and that we reduce our deficit in a balanced way that allows us to make these critical investments.

name: audio38.wav
speaker: SPEAKER_00
text: Now, ultimately, it's going to be up to the voters, to you, which path we should take.

name: audio39.wav
speaker: SPEAKER_00
text: Are we going to double down on the top-down economic policies that helped to get us into this mess, or do we embrace a new economic patriotism that says America does best when the middle class does best?

name: audio40.wav
speaker: SPEAKER_00
text: And I'm looking forward to having that debate.

name: audio41.wav
speaker: SPEAKER_00

speaker: SPEAKER_02
